## What this project is

`logproxy.py` is a **transparent analytical forward-proxy** between the `claude`
CLI and `https://api.anthropic.com`. The CLI is pointed at it via
`ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL`. It forwards bytes verbatim and **captures** every
request + response so we can study agentic traffic. **Primary mission: find and
price context waste; stay non-intrusive (no visible overhead).** Secondary:
reliable cost tracking; discover useful response data.

## The thesis we proved (with live data)

**Cost is context carriage, not "the model thinking."** Across an 18-turn
trivial session: context carriage (input+cache_read+cache_write) = **$2.72**;
actual model output (950 tokens) = **$0.07**. Carriage is **38× the cost / 618×
the tokens** of the work. `cache_read` = the *same ~38k context re-shipped every
turn* (the "sent over and over"). Steady-state warm turn: ~93% of cost is just
re-reading cached context; ~62% of that is **deadweight** (loaded-but-unused
tools + agent roster).

Key corollaries, all measured:
- **"Cached so it's cheap" is backwards.** The right baseline for junk context
  is *zero*, not its uncached price — so cache bills you 10% of something that
  should be 0, *every turn, forever*. Cached content is **still fully in the
  payload** (we verified: a turn with `cache_read=38,261, input=2` still
  physically ships all 31 tool schemas, ~105KB). Caching discounts compute
  price only — NOT bandwidth, NOT context-window occupancy/attention.
- **Deadweight is real:** a "2+2" turn loaded **31 tools (~23k tok), used 0**
  (`tool_uses=[]`), plus a ~2.4k-tok "Available agent types" roster — all cached
  & re-read every turn.

## Code state (logproxy.py) — what's been built

1. **Per-session output dirs.** `LOG_DIR/<session_id>/` for `messages`;
   `LOG_DIR/_no-session/` for count_tokens/probes; `LOG_DIR/_totals.json`
   global + `<session>/_session.json` per-session. Files:
   `<seq>-<agent>-<role>-<model>-<HHMMSS>.{request.json,response.json,response.sse}`.
2. **All disk I/O off the hot path** — single background daemon writer thread +
   queue (`_writer_loop`, `_enqueue_json/_enqueue_bytes`). Handler only parses +
   enqueues. `atexit` flush. This is the "non-intrusive" requirement.
3. **session_id parsing** (`_session_ids`): it's nested — `metadata.user_id` is
   itself a JSON string `{"device_id","account_uuid","session_id"}`.
4. **Inbound transport capture**: `client` (host:port) + `request_headers`
   (secrets redacted via `_SECRET_HEADERS` / `_safe_headers`).
5. **EXPERIMENTAL injection** (off by default). `_decide_injection` picks what to
   append to the last **user** message (scans backward — `messages[-1]` is often a
   trailing system catalog, not the prompt). Two modes:
   - `INJECT` set → **unconditional** append every turn (legacy piggyback testbed).
   - `INJECT_MARKER` set → **marker-gated**: append `INJECT_TEXT` (default
     "Also, what is 23 × 19?", sep `INJECT_SEP`) ONLY when the user's prompt
     contains the marker substring (e.g. `Math:`). Lets the human opt a turn into
     enhancement via a natural keyword; mundane turns pass through untouched.
   - `INJECT_FILE=<path>` set → **volunteer-context**: append the file's CURRENT
     on-disk contents (read fresh, ≤`INJECT_FILE_MAX_BYTES`) as an authoritative
     `<system-reminder>` — but ONLY on genuine prompt turns (last user msg has
     text), NOT on tool_result continuation hops. Priority: file > marker > INJECT.
     `INJECT_FILE_NOTE` (optional) folds an operating instruction into that
     system-reminder — e.g. "you have the exact bytes, edit via Bash not Edit" —
     which is how `mutate-bypass` collapses the mutation Read (see SKIP-THE-READ).
   Re-encodes only when it actually changes. Logs an `injection` record
   (`reason`, `marker`, `original_last_user`, `final_last_user`) in request.json.
   NOTE: the marker fires on EVERY request whose last user text contains it —
   including the CLI's separate haiku "title generation" meta-call (it embeds the
   prompt). Scope to `role==parent` downstream if a scenario needs only the main turn.

6. **EXPERIMENTAL response mutation** (off by default) — edits what comes BACK,
   not just the request. `RESP_APPEND` adds a text_delta into the LAST text block
   (concatenates onto the visible answer); `RESP_REPLACE="old\x1fnew"` swaps text
   inside every text_delta. Implementation: buffer the full SSE, rewrite at
   event granularity (`_mutate_sse`/`_data_of`), emit once (loses streaming —
   fine for experiments). Writes `<stem>.response.mutated.sse` + a
   `response_injection` note. MUST target TEXT blocks, never THINKING (block 0
   was thinking in tests; thinking blocks carry signatures — leave them alone).

   **PROVEN (2026-06-02): the CLI accepts altered responses with ZERO pushback**
   — no signature/integrity check on text. REPLACE: model said "Paris" → proxy
   "LONDON" → CLI displayed "LONDON", is_error=false. APPEND: "hello world" →
   "hello world [proxy-appended]". **And response edits PERSIST into the
   transcript** (asymmetry vs request injection, which desyncs): a turn-2 resume
   asked "what did you just tell me?" and the model answered "LONDON" — it
   believes it said the altered text. So response mutation is DURABLE
   conversation state, whereas request injection is transient. (This reopens the
   transcript/readFileState-seed question we'd written off — the transcript now
   reflects proxy-altered content.)

7. **EXPERIMENTAL turn short-circuit** (off by default) — elides the post-edit
   "wrap-up" round trip. Why it exists: a response containing a `tool_use` always
   gets `stop_reason:"tool_use"` (= "run this, I'll continue"), so even a
   SUCCESSFUL TERMINAL edit STILL costs a whole turn just to hear the model say
   "Done." The wire format has NO "last action" flag — that trailing turn
   re-ships the full context (~one cache_read carriage, ~34.9k tok) to produce a
   ~20-tok ack. We supply the missing affordance: `SHORTCIRCUIT_DONE=<sentinel>`
   (e.g. `<DONE>`) enables it; `SHORTCIRCUIT_ACK` (default "Done.") is the
   synthetic reply; `SHORTCIRCUIT_TOOLS` is the terminal-tool allowlist.
   `_shortcircuit_decision` fires ONLY when the request is the tool_result
   continuation of a single SUCCESSFUL terminal tool_use whose preceding
   assistant message carries the sentinel in TEXT, with matching tool_use_id.
   Then `_synth_end_turn_sse` builds a valid end_turn SSE and the handler RETURNS
   IT WITHOUT CALLING UPSTREAM (logs a `shortcircuit` record, `response.json`
   has `billing:null`). The edit already happened client-side before this
   request, so nothing is lost but the round trip. Refuses to fire on an ERROR
   tool_result (model must react). **VALIDATED (2026-06-02, `shortcircuit`
   scenario):** CLI transparently accepts the fully-synthetic end_turn (same as
   the LONDON finding); fired 1/1 with the forceful prompt, docstring correct,
   file intact, wrap-up turn = 0 tokens, API saw 1 parent turn not 2.

   **VALIDATED INTERACTIVE (2026-06-02, live `claude` on :7803, 2-edit session):
   it CHAINS.** Edit#1 → SC fired (synthetic "Done."); follow-up turn → model
   (a) correctly RECALLED what it changed (synthetic "Done." did not corrupt its
   history sense), (b) AUTO-CARRIED the `<DONE>` protocol from conversation
   history without being re-instructed, so Edit#2 also emitted text+`<DONE>` →
   **SC fired AGAIN, stacking on top of the prior synthetic turn**, no corruption.
   Caching unharmed: the edit turn AFTER a short-circuit still hit the prefix
   cache (`cache_read` = the cold prefix from the first edit). So: teach the
   convention once, elide every terminal-edit wrap-up thereafter. Combined with
   `@file` (collapses the Read), a plain 3-turn edit task (Read→Edit→Done) drops
   to 1 real parent turn ≈ **−66% carriage** in this minimal session (each turn
   re-ships ~equal ~35k; the absolute saving is "2 deleted round trips," so the
   % shrinks as a session lengthens). NOTE the CLI fires its own tiny title-gen
   meta call(s) that EMBED the prompt (out~16 tok) — constant overhead, ignore.

   **THREE-WAY INTERACTIVE A/B MEASURED (2026-06-02, identical 2-task session:
   docstring + comment-above-fn, haiku):**
     - baseline (plain path, no SC): 2 Reads, 6 work turns (Read→Edit→Done ×2),
       **206,170 tok**
     - `@` only (no SC):             0 Reads, 4 work turns (Edit→Done ×2),
       **137,807 tok**
     - `@` + shortcircuit:           0 Reads, 2 work turns (Edit ×2),
       **70,149 tok**
   File correct in all three. The two levers are CO-EQUAL HALVES (each deletes 2
   turns of ~34k):
     - `@` removes the 2 Read turns:        206,170 → 137,807 = **−68,363 (−33.2%)**
     - SC removes the 2 wrap-up turns (atop `@`): 137,807 → 70,149 = **−67,658
       (−49.1% of the @-only cost; −32.8% of baseline)**
     - combined: **−136,021 = −66.0%**.
   Takeaway: `@` (free, native, zero-risk) buys the first ~33%; SC (proxy,
   assume-success tradeoff) buys the second ~33%. `@`-only is the safe sweet spot;
   SC is the extra third you pay a little correctness risk for. Sessions:
   baseline 71bfe025, @-only 6aa81a3b, @+SC 2754aab8 (logs_inject).

   **THE HARD PART IS THE SIGNAL TIMING, not the mechanism (key finding).** With
   extended thinking on, the model emits `[thinking, BARE tool_use]` at edit time
   — NO text block — and writes `<DONE>` only on the WRAP-UP turn (the very turn
   we want to elide). I.e. **the model naturally REFUSES to declare "done" before
   it sees the edit succeed** — empirically the same correctness boundary we
   reasoned about. A light "say <DONE> when finished" note ⇒ 0 fires. To win you
   must FORCE a text block carrying the sentinel in the SAME message as the Edit
   AND tell it to ASSUME success (predict terminality, don't confirm it) — that's
   the `_SC_NOTE` protocol prompt in experiments.py. Tradeoffs: (a) you're now
   asking the model to predict success — safe only for atomic single edits; (b)
   the sentinel shows in the user-visible text of the edit turn (cosmetic; a
   production client would STRIP it while tracking the tool_use_id in memory to
   keep detection — can't strip via wire-history since the CLI replays the
   stripped text); (c) you replace the model's real post-edit SUMMARY with a
   canned "Done." — ceremony for automation, mild value for an interactive user.
   Also note: thinking blocks are STRIPPED from replayed history (the assistant
   msg the detector sees on the wrap-up request is just `[tool_use]`), so the
   sentinel MUST be in a real text block, never thinking.

8. **RELAY mode** (`SHORTCIRCUIT_RELAY=1`, requires `SHORTCIRCUIT_DONE`) — instead
   of a canned "Done.", REPLAY the model's OWN pre-written summary. Justified
   because for an authored mutation like `Edit` the success result is
   INFORMATION-FREE: the model already knows the post-edit file byte-for-byte
   (it wrote old→new); the result is just a pass/fail bit (and we gate on it).
   `_relay_capture_and_strip` (edit turn): if the response has one terminal
   tool_use + a text block with the sentinel, STASH the cleaned prose keyed by
   `tool_use_id` and REMOVE that text block (reindexing later blocks — must
   REMOVE, not blank: an EMPTY text block → API 400 "text content blocks must be
   non-empty" when replayed). `_shortcircuit_relay_decision` (wrap-up): on a
   SUCCESS tool_result whose id we stashed, replay the prose; on ERROR, discard +
   forward normally. This also lets us STRIP the sentinel cleanly (detection is
   by id, not by reading `<DONE>` from history) → nothing leaks to the user.
   VALIDATED interactively: clean past-tense summary appears once, 0 API trip.
   **UX CHARACTERISTIC (live A/B, 2026-06-03):** the relayed text is the model's
   DISPATCH-TIME summary (authored as it issued the Edit, BEFORE seeing the result),
   whereas a non-proxy baseline summarizes on the wrap-up turn WITH the result in
   hand. Observed: proxy "Added a module-level docstring to sample.py." vs baseline
   "Added a module-level docstring … describing the helpers and the script's CLI
   behavior." So relayed summaries skew TERSER / less final-state-grounded — a
   plausibly SYSTEMATIC bias (pre-result authoring) on top of sampling noise; n=1
   can't separate them. Cosmetic, both correct; if it ever matters, drop RELAY (use
   canned ack) or let that one wrap-up run. Do NOT record as "proven identical."
   **⚠ RELAY IS BUGGY ON MULTI-STEP / RESUMED BUILDS — DO NOT USE IT THERE; use
   canned-ack SC (2026-06-03).** On the spec-build sonnet run, relay's edit-turn
   STRIP (removing the sentinel-bearing text block from the dispatch response the
   CLI sees) makes the CLI REJECT the subsequent relay-synthetic end_turn and
   RE-SEND an IDENTICAL tool_result continuation (verified: requests 004 & 005 both
   `last_role=user blocks=[tool_result] nmsgs=3`). The proxy already popped the
   tid on the first fire, so the duplicate falls through UPSTREAM → a real wrap-up
   turn anyway → SC "fired" 2× but parent_turns stayed 6 and tokens went UP +0.8%.
   The CANNED-ACK path (no strip) does NOT duplicate: same build, relay OFF →
   6→3 turns, 3/3 fired, −49.5% tok. ROOT CAUSE (unconfirmed but strongly implied):
   the strip leaves the dispatch assistant msg as `[tool_use]`-only in the CLI's
   view, and the relay-synthetic end_turn that follows is rejected/retried by the
   headless CLI; the trivial single-`-p` canned path never strips so never trips it.
   TODO if relay UX is ever wanted on builds: capture the duplicate-trigger (diff
   the relay-synthetic SSE vs a real end_turn the CLI accepts) — but canned-ack is
   the clean default and loses only the model's own-prose summary (cosmetic).

9. **DELIVERY / UX of the protocol (how to make it invisible) — measured.** The
   hard part is reliably getting the model to emit the summary+sentinel AT
   DISPATCH (same message as the Edit). Governing principle: **the signal must be
   framed as a THIS-TURN output-format directive, not a post-tool condition** —
   anything that reads as "when the tool completes/ after it returns" makes the
   model DEFER `<DONE>` to the wrap-up turn (too late, the turn we wanted to cut).
   Fire rates (plain user prompt; protocol delivered via the named channel):
     - `SHORTCIRCUIT_INSTRUCT` (tail-append to USER msg, imperative "in the SAME
