## Hard technical facts we learned (don't re-derive)

- **Message structure:** user's prompt is in `messages[0]` (a system-reminder
  text block + the actual question text block). A `role:system` catalog
  ("Available agent types…", ~7k chars / ~1.7k tok) is appended **after** it.
- **New CLI (claude-cli 2.1.x) emits NO `count_tokens`** — only `messages`. So
  `_no-session` is mostly just `/` health probes now (the historic 254
  count_tokens were an older sonnet CLI).
- **Cache tiers differ by lifecycle:** main agent caches at **1h** (2×, durable
  for think-time); **subagents cache at 5m** (1.25×, cheaper, ephemeral). Set
  via `cache_control` breakpoints in the payload (1h has `ttl:'1h'`; 5m omits
  ttl).
- **Caching is prefix-based.** Tail edits (last user msg) are cache-safe; system/
  tools/history edits bust the cache downstream.
- **Subagents share the parent's `session_id`** — a session dir is really a
  *conversation tree* (parent + subagents). Distinguish them by `role`
  (`_classify_role`) and tool set. So per-subagent analysis = group by
  (session, role), NOT session alone.
- **Subagent cache economics (measured):** 1st spawn of a type = COLD (writes
  its own ~9–10k shell). Re-spawn SAME type within 5m = WARM (`cache_read` hit,
  ~4.7× cheaper). New/different type = COLD again. Plan shell=9 tools, ~9,195
  tok; general-purpose=12 tools, ~10,235 tok; `claude`/general-purpose grant
  `*` (full ~31-tool set). Intermittent background spawns (>5m apart) cold-start
  every time (5m TTL lapses) → cost-saving from cache reuse only happens for
  bursty same-type spawns. Context-preservation benefit (main grows ~480 tok =
  just the result) holds regardless.

## Round-trip / injection findings (the active frontier)

- **The real cost lever is round-trip reduction.** Agentic loops (read→edit→test)
  re-ship the full growing context each hop. Two reducible classes:
  - **Independent fan-out** → batchable as parallel `tool_use` in ONE response
    (one response CAN carry multiple `tool_use` blocks; `meta.tool_uses` is a
    list). The waste is when the model *serializes* independent calls.
  - **Dependent chains** → NOT batchable (step N+1 needs step N's output); only
    **speculation/injection** can cut these, at a correctness cost (the round
    trip you delete *is* the verification step).
- **PROVEN: payload piggyback works + the client does NOT police free-text
  responses.** We injected "compute 3+3 → INJECTED-PROBE: 3+3=<result>" into a
  "2+2" turn; model returned `2 + 2 = 4\n\nINJECTED-PROBE: 3+3=6`; the CLI
  displayed it verbatim, no scrub/error. So: payload-inject → model-comply →
  client-display is a clean pipeline (for the free-text path).
- **State drift confirmed:** CLI's history keeps the original user text but
  records the assistant's injected answer → conversation desyncs. Fine for
  transient single-shot; compounds otherwise.

## SKIP-THE-READ: RESOLVED (2026-06-02, `INJECT_FILE` + file-extract experiment)

Built the `INJECT_FILE` "volunteer context" mode and ran it (proxy-experiments
`file-extract`). Result splits by task type:
- **Extraction/Q&A turn → WIN.** Volunteering the file as a tail system-reminder
  let the agent answer with `meta.tool_uses == []` — it skipped `Glob`+`Read`
  entirely. Clean round-trip collapse, no quality loss.
- **Mutation turn → no win (can hurt).** Agent did `Edit`(fail)→`Read`→`Edit`.

**The real gate (traced in CLI source, not the `old_string` match):**
`FileEditTool.validateInput` checks `toolUseContext.readFileState.get(path)`
BEFORE old_string — empty ⇒ `errorCode 6` "File has not been read yet" (behavior
`ask`). `readFileState` is a **client-side cache written in 6 local spots
(Read/Write/Edit/NotebookEdit/Bash/attachments), none on the API wire.** So a
transparent proxy CANNOT forge it in a live session; the read-before-edit hop is
a deliberate integrity invariant, not waste. The only bridge is
`extractReadFilesFromMessages` on resume/seed paths (`restoreReadFileState`,
headless `print.ts` "seed from transcript") — but it seeds from the CLI's LOCAL
transcript, which (per our desync finding) never contains wire-injected content.
⇒ **proxy-based forged-Read-pair is a predictable NULL; don't run it.** (Full
mechanism + the exact forged-pair shape, for transcript-level use only, is in
proxy-experiments/CLAUDE.md.)

**BUT the mutation Read IS collapsible — by tool substitution, not wire forgery
(`mutate-bypass` experiment, validated).** The gate is `FileEditTool`-specific;
`Bash`/`Write` have no read-precondition. Volunteer byte-exact content +
`INJECT_FILE_NOTE` = "you have the exact bytes, edit via Bash, no need to Read" →
agent does `Bash`-only (0 Reads), edits correctly, **−32.6% tokens**. Cost: you
trade away the read-before-edit integrity invariant (safe only while volunteered
content is byte-exact & fresh) and must allow `Bash`.

Even cleaner than the Bash-bypass: a **custom read-internally edit tool** (MCP
`edit`, `proxy-experiments/mcp_update_server.py`) — the read-before-edit bounce is
FileEditTool policy, so a tool that just reads the file itself removes the round
trip AND keeps integrity (matches current bytes, fails loudly on mismatch).
Initial run showed an edit-QUALITY regression, which I wrongly blamed on "tool
unfamiliarity / missing-Read grounding." **RESOLVED: it was purely the tool
DEFINITION.** A tool is just a name+description+schema the client ships (a prompt
we control); there is nothing innate. We pulled the CLI's real `Edit` definition
off the wire and gave our tool the same contract → **3/3 clean wins**: docstring
correctly placed, file intact, 0 Reads, −31% tokens. The Read round trip is
recoverable overhead, NOT load-bearing grounding.

REFRAME: this is **prototyping a CLIENT optimization** (read buffer client-side,
hand the edit tool the bytes, keep the checks, drop the model-facing Read turn).
Proxy + MCP tool are stand-ins; conclusions transfer to a real client change.

Mission takeaway: volunteering byte-exact context wins the round trip for BOTH
read-only turns and mutation turns (~31-33%/turn) via tool substitution — no
`readFileState` forgery needed. With a CLI-parity edit tool that reads its own
buffer, mutation is a CLEAN win (no quality loss, no corruption risk); the Bash
variant works too but trades the integrity invariant.

**NATIVE ANSWER (use this, not the proxy): `@file`.** The CLI input pipeline
reads `@path`, inlines it, AND writes `readFileState` (attachment processing is
one of the 6 writers). So `@sample.py` → 0 Reads, Edit runs directly (gate
satisfied), −33% tokens, fully safe. Validated (`at-mention`). Most of our
injection backflips were reinventing `@`. Volunteering just the PATH (no `@`)
does NOT help — the model still Reads. So: use native `@`/`!`/`/`/hooks for
context & read-collapse; reserve the PROXY for what only a wire intermediary can
do — turn-collapse (request piggyback) and DURABLE response mutation.

